## Diagnosis

The `micro` rendering mode was introduced to "fit" text into small tiles by shrinking the font to 8px. This is a classic legibility anti-pattern: the text becomes unreadable, so the component is communicating nothing useful to the user while creating visual noise.

Small tiles don't have enough room to display a label legibly — the correct response is to **hide the label entirely**, not shrink it past the threshold of readability.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072: Progressively-degraded-to-illegible text** — using font scaling as a progressive disclosure strategy past the point of legibility. The component treats font size as a continuous knob rather than a boolean "show or hide" decision at a minimum readable size.

The `micro` mode likely looks something like this in the component:

```tsx
// KnowledgeTreemap.tsx  — BEFORE (anti-pattern)
const getLabelMode = (width: number, height: number) => {
  const area = width * height;
  if (area < 32 * 32) return 'hidden';
  if (width < 64)     return 'micro';   // ← the offender
  if (width < 120)    return 'compact';
  return 'full';
};

// rendered as:
{mode === 'micro' && (
  <text fontSize={8} ...>{category}</text>   // unreadable
)}
```

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` mode entirely

**`components/KnowledgeTreemap/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx`**

```tsx
// ─── BEFORE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
type LabelMode = 'hidden' | 'micro' | 'compact' | 'full';

const getLabelMode = (width: number, height: number): LabelMode => {
  const area = width * height;
  if (area < 32 * 32) return 'hidden';
  if (width < 64)     return 'micro';
  if (width < 120)    return 'compact';
  return 'full';
};

// ─── AFTER ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
type LabelMode = 'hidden' | 'compact' | 'full';

// Minimum dimensions for a label to be legible at normal size.
// Compact = icon or abbreviation only; Full = icon + full label.
const MIN_LABEL_WIDTH  = 64;   // px — enough for ~6 chars at body-sm
const MIN_LABEL_HEIGHT = 32;   // px — enough for one line of text

const getLabelMode = (width: number, height: number): LabelMode => {
  if (width < MIN_LABEL_WIDTH || height < MIN_LABEL_HEIGHT) return 'hidden';
  if (width < 120) return 'compact';
  return 'full';
};
```

### 2. Fix the render switch — no 8px font, ever

```tsx
// ─── BEFORE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const TileLabel = ({ mode, category, icon }: TileLabelProps) => {
  if (mode === 'hidden') return null;
  if (mode === 'micro')  return (
    <text
      fontSize={8}          // ← illegible
      fill="currentColor"
      textAnchor="middle"
    >
      {category.slice(0, 1)}
    </text>
  );
  // … compact / full …
};

// ─── AFTER ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const TileLabel = ({ mode, category, icon }: TileLabelProps) => {
  // 'micro' is gone — the only permitted modes are hidden | compact | full.
  if (mode === 'hidden') return null;

  if (mode === 'compact') return (
    // Icon only (or first character as a badge), at normal body-sm size.
    // Never go below the design system's smallest legible token (text-xs / 12px).
    <text
      fontSize={12}         // design-system: --text-xs
      fontWeight={600}
      fill="currentColor"
      textAnchor="middle"
      dominantBaseline="middle"
    >
      {icon ?? category.slice(0, 1).toUpperCase()}
    </text>
  );

  return (
    // Full label at normal body size.
    <text
      fontSize={14}         // design-system: --text-sm
      fontWeight={500}
      fill="currentColor"
      textAnchor="middle"
      dominantBaseline="middle"
    >
      {category}
    </text>
  );
};
```

### 3. Update the type export so consumers can't pass `'micro'`

**`components/KnowledgeTreemap/types.ts`**

```ts
// ─── BEFORE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export type LabelMode = 'hidden' | 'micro' | 'compact' | 'full';

// ─── AFTER ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
/** Describes how a treemap tile label is rendered.
 *  'hidden'  — tile too small; no label rendered.
 *  'compact' — icon or single glyph at minimum legible size (12px / text-xs).
 *  'full'    — full category name at body size (14px / text-sm).
 *
 *  There is intentionally no 'micro' mode. Sub-12px text is never permitted
 *  in the Elan design system — hide the label instead.
 */
export type LabelMode = 'hidden' | 'compact' | 'full';
```

### 4. Add a guardrail test

**`components/KnowledgeTreemap/KnowledgeTreemap.test.tsx`**

```tsx
describe('KnowledgeTreemap – label legibility guardrail', () => {
  it('never renders a font smaller than 12px regardless of tile size', () => {
    const { container } = render(
      <KnowledgeTreemap
        data={mockData}
        width={400}
        height={300}
      />
    );
    const textNodes = container.querySelectorAll('text');
    textNodes.forEach((node) => {
      const fs = parseFloat(node.getAttribute('fontSize') ?? '14');
      expect(fs).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(12);
    });
  });

  it('hides the label rather than shrinking it for tiles narrower than 64px', () => {
    // Force a layout where at least one tile is narrow.
    const tinyData = [{ name: 'X', value: 1 }, { name: 'Large', value: 999 }];
    const { container } = render(
      <KnowledgeTreemap data={tinyData} width={300} height={300} />
    );
    // The tiny tile must have no <text> child.
    const tiles = container.querySelectorAll('[data-tile]');
    tiles.forEach((tile) => {
      const rect  = tile.querySelector('rect')!;
      const width = parseFloat(rect.getAttribute('width') ?? '999');
      if (width < 64) {
        expect(tile.querySelector('text')).toBeNull();
      }
    });
  });
});
```

---

## Principle

> **Labels are binary: either legible at their normal size, or absent. Font size is not a progressive disclosure knob.**

Concretely for the Elan system:

| Tile condition | Label treatment |
|---|---|
| Too small to hold a legible glyph | `hidden` — render nothing |
| Enough room for one glyph / icon | `compact` — icon or initial at `text-xs` (12px min) |
| Full room | `full` — category name at `text-sm` (14px) |

The floor of **12px** (`--text-xs`) is a hard constraint in Elan. Nothing in the system should ever output a font below that value — put it in your design token linting rules (`stylelint` / token-validator) and in the test above so it can never be reintroduced silently.

The underlying engineering rule is: **when content doesn't fit its container, omit it — don't degrade it**. This maps to the same principle as responsive image `srcset` (serve no image rather than a 4×4 blur) and truncated text with `…` (truncate rather than reflow at 6px). Fitting-by-shrinking shifts the cost of the layout problem onto the reader's eyes.
